sec.p:
Finally, we have assumed that defenders are harmed but not killed by the attack. Killing is more than a large welfare loss; it also alters the strategic structure of future rounds, by removing some actors. In particular, allowing defenders to be killed would bring the partner effect into play (Eshel and Shaked 2001): each death shrinks the group, and therefore increases the probability that an individual survivor will be targeted in a given round. At large group sizes, this effect is negligible (since 

1N≈1N−1

), but at smaller group sizes it would strengthen the incentive to help.
